&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 1.3%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: medium none valign=bottom width=1% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 9.66%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: medium none valign=bottom width=9% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: right align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;2.32&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 0.68%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=0% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The weighted average grant-date fair value of options granted during the years ended December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011 was $3.57 and $2.44 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The intrinsic value related to total stock options outstanding was $3.8 million as of December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and $2.3 million as of December&amp;#160;31
 2011.&amp;#160; The intrinsic value related to vested stock options outstanding was $2.6 million as of December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and $1.7 million as of December&amp;#160;31
 2011.&amp;#160; The aggregate intrinsic value is based on the exercise price and our closing stock price of $6.31 as of December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and $3.74 as of December&amp;#160;31
 2011.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Treasury Stock&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Our Board of Directors approved a stock repurchase program that was publicly announced on Form&amp;#160;8-K filed with the SEC on June&amp;#160;21
 2011 whereby up to $3 million of common stock could be purchased from time to time at the discretion of management (the &amp;#8220;2011 program&amp;#8221;).&amp;#160; The 2011 program expired on June&amp;#160;20
 2012.&amp;#160; No shares were repurchased under the 2011 program.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;9.&amp;#160; Income Taxes:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The provision for income taxes consisted of the following for the years ended December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: windowtext 1pt solid; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 15.34%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 1pt solid valign=bottom width=15% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: right align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;(2
783
755&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 1pt; WIDTH: 1.3%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=1% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We had federal income taxes receivable of $0.6 million and $0.4 million as of December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 respectively.&amp;#160; We had a state income tax liability of $0.1 million and a state income tax receivable of $0.2 million as of December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Generally accepted accounting principles require that a valuation allowance be established when it is more-likely-than-not that all or a portion of a deferred tax asset will not be realized.&amp;#160; Changes in valuation allowances from period to period are included in the tax provision in the period of change.&amp;#160; In determining whether a valuation allowance is required
 we take into account all positive and negative evidence with regard to the utilization of a deferred tax asset including our past earnings history
 expected future earnings
 the character and jurisdiction of such earnings
 unsettled circumstances that
 if unfavorably resolved
 would adversely affect utilization of a deferred tax asset
 carryback and carryforward periods and tax strategies that could potentially enhance the likelihood of realization of a deferred tax asset.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The following table provides a reconciliation between the amount determined by applying the statutory federal income tax rate to our income tax provision for fiscal years ended December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;10.&amp;#160; Business Segments and Significant Customers:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;For the years ended December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 Costco was the only customer accounting for more than 10% of our total net revenue.&amp;#160; Costco accounted for $64.6 million or 35% and $49.3 million or 30%
 for fiscal years 2012 and 2011
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center align=center&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Our operations consist of two reportable segments: snack products and frozen products.&amp;#160; The snack products segment produces potato chips
 potato crisps
 potato skins
 pellet snacks
 kettle chips
 and extruded product for sale primarily to snack food distributors and retailers.&amp;#160; This segment includes a limited number of snack food products purchased and sold through our local distribution network in Arizona.&amp;#160; As part of the sale of our DSD business discussed in Note 1
 we no longer sell distributed products
 which were $2.6 million in 2012.&amp;#160; The frozen products segment produces frozen fruit products
 such as berries and smoothies
 for sale primarily to club stores
 groceries and mass merchandisers.&amp;#160; Our reportable segments offer different products and services.&amp;#160; The majority of our revenues are attributable to external customers in the United States.&amp;#160; We sell to external customers internationally
 however the revenues attributable to those customers are immaterial.&amp;#160; All of our assets are located in the United States.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The accounting policies of the segments are the same as those described in the Summary of Significant Accounting Policies (Note 1).&amp;#160; We do not allocate assets
 selling
 general and administrative expenses
 income taxes or other income and expense to segments.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;11.&amp;#160; Litigation:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We are periodically a party to various lawsuits arising in the ordinary course of business.&amp;#160; Management believes
 based on discussions with legal counsel
 that the resolution of any such lawsuits
 individually and in the aggregate
&amp;#160;will not have a material adverse effect on our financial position or results of operations.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;In March&amp;#160;2012
 we learned that the Jamba Juice Company was named as a defendant in a putative class action filed in the Federal Court for the North District of California and captioned Kevin Anderson v. Jamba Juice Company which claims that the use of the words &amp;#8220;all natural&amp;#8221; to describe the Smoothie Kits is misleading and deceptive to consumers and violates various California consumer protection statutes and unfair competition statutes.&amp;#160; The suit is one of several &amp;#8220;all natural&amp;#8221; lawsuits recently brought against various food manufacturers and distributors in California.&amp;#160; In an amended complaint the plaintiff also alleged violations of the federal Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act
 but the court dismissed those claims in a ruling issued in August&amp;#160;2012.&amp;#160; In a second amended complaint filed in September&amp;#160;2012
 we were added as a defendant.&amp;#160; Under our license agreement with the Jamba Juice Company
 we are obligated and have agreed to indemnify and defend Jamba Juice in the suit
 and Jamba has tendered defense of the claim to us.&amp;#160; While we currently believe the &amp;#8220;all natural&amp;#8221; claims on the Smoothie Kits are not misleading and in full compliance with FDA guidelines
 we are investigating the claims asserted in the action
 and intend to vigorously defend against them.&amp;#160; The plaintiff is seeking to certify a class of all persons in California who bought certain of the Jamba Juice Smoothie Kits
 and the plaintiff&amp;#8217;s deadline for filing a motion for class certification is April&amp;#160;1
 2013.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;12.&amp;#160; Related Party Transactions:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We own a farming
 processing and storage facility located on 696 acres of land in Lynden
 Washington
 which is leased from the Uptrails Group LLC
 owned by three members of the Rader family.&amp;#160; One of the three
 Brad Rader
 is a current employee of ours and one of the others
 Sue Rader
 was a former owner of Rader Farms.&amp;#160; This operating lease commenced on the acquisition date and was extended in October&amp;#160;2012 through May&amp;#160;17
 2027.&amp;#160; Lease payments are $43
500 per month through May&amp;#160;17
 2017 at which time they increase to $52
200 for the duration of the term of the lease.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Effective January&amp;#160;13
 2013
 a member of our Board of Directors was named Chief Executive Officer of Bland Farms
&amp;#160;Inc.
 the parent company of Vidalia Brands
&amp;#160;Inc.
 with whom we have a broker agreement and a license to sell our Vidalia&amp;#174; brand snack products.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;13.&amp;#160; Accounts Receivable Allowance:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;14.&amp;#160; Concentrations of Credit Risk:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We maintain most of our cash with one financial institution.&amp;#160; As of November&amp;#160;1
 2008 the FDIC introduced the transaction guarantee program which guaranteed non-interest bearing accounts without limit.&amp;#160; The FDIC program is temporary and only offered through participating financial institutions.&amp;#160; Our primary financial institution participated in this program and therefore all cash balances held with this institution as of December&amp;#160;29
 2012 are insured.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Our primary concentration of credit risk is related to certain trade accounts receivable.&amp;#160; In the normal course of business
 we extend unsecured credit to our customers.&amp;#160; We investigate a customer&amp;#8217;s credit worthiness before extending credit.&amp;#160; At December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 three customers accounted for 48% and 39% of accounts receivable
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;15.&amp;#160; Deferred Compensation Plans&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We have contributory 401(k)&amp;#160;plans covering substantially all employees.&amp;#160; We may contribute amounts not in excess of the lesser of the maximum deductions allowable for income tax purposes or a specific percentage of our operating profits
 as defined in the plan.&amp;#160; We made contributions totaling $0.4 million during the years ending December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We also sponsor a trusteed
 nonqualified savings plan for employees whose contributions to a tax qualified 401(k)&amp;#160;plan would be limited by provisions of the Internal Revenue Code.&amp;#160; The plan allows participants to defer receipt of a portion of their salary and incentive compensation.&amp;#160; The plan was amended in 2009 and we no longer match any employee contributions to this plan.&amp;#160; Participants earn a return on their deferred compensation based on investment earnings of participant-selected mutual funds.&amp;#160; Deferred compensation
 including accumulated earnings on the participant-directed investment selections
 is distributable in cash at participant-specified dates or upon retirement
 death
 disability or termination of employment.&amp;#160; At December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 the plan&amp;#8217;s assets and our liability to participants of the deferred compensation plans was $0.4 million
 and is recorded in other assets and other liabilities in the Consolidated Balance Sheets.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;16.&amp;#160; Quarterly Financial Data (Unaudited):&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 1%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

  
  

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Principles of Consolidation&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of Inventure Foods
&amp;#160;Inc. and all of its wholly owned subsidiaries.&amp;#160; All significant intercompany amounts and transactions have been eliminated.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Use of Estimates&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities
 disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements
 and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period.&amp;#160; We routinely evaluate our estimates
 including those related to accruals for customer programs and incentives
 product returns
 bad debts
 income taxes
 long-lived assets
 inventories
 stock based compensation
 interest rate swap valuations
 accrued broker commissions and contingencies.&amp;#160; We base our estimates on historical experience and on various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable under the circumstances.&amp;#160; Actual results could differ from those estimates.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Fair Value of Financial Instruments&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.4in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Fair value is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability (i.e.
 the &amp;#8220;exit price&amp;#8221;)&amp;#160; in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date.&amp;#160; W&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt size=2&gt;e classify our investments based upon an established fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to valuation techniques used to measure fair value.&amp;#160; The hierarchy gives the highest priority to unadjusted quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities (Level 1 measurement) and the lowest priority to unobservable inputs (Level 3 measurements).&amp;#160; The three levels of the fair value hierarchy are described as follows:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.4in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 1.1in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.7in&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Level 1&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt size=2&gt;Unadjusted quoted prices in active markets that are accessible at the measurement date for identical
 unrestricted assets or liabilities;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 1.1in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.7in&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Level 2&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt size=2&gt;Quoted prices in markets that are not considered to be active or financial instruments without quoted market prices
 but for which all significant inputs are observable
 either directly or indirectly;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 1.1in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.7in&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Level 3&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 3pt size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt size=2&gt;Prices or valuations that require inputs that are both significant to the fair value measurement and unobservable.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 1.4in; TEXT-INDENT: -1in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.4in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;A financial instrument&amp;#8217;s level within the fair value hierarchy is based on the lowest level of any input that is significant to the fair value measurement.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.4in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;At December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 the carrying value of cash
 accounts receivable
 accounts payable and accrued liabilities approximate fair values since they are short-term in nature.&amp;#160; The carrying value of the long-term debt approximates fair-value based on the borrowing rates currently available to us for long-term borrowings with similar terms.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table style=WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=100% border=0&gt;
&lt;tr style=HEIGHT: 0px&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 32.5%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=32%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 2.5%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=2%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center align=center&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 10%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=10%&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=1&gt;Balance&amp;#160;Sheet&amp;#160;Classification&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 2.5%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=2%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center align=center&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 10%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=10%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center align=center&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 2.5%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=2%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center align=center&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 11%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 1pt solid valign=bottom width=11% colspan=2&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center align=center&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 8pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=1&gt;Interest&amp;#160;Rate&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;#160;Swaps&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 2.5%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=2%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 11%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 1pt solid valign=bottom width=11% colspan=2&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 11%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 1pt solid valign=bottom width=11% colspan=2&gt;

&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 11%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 1pt solid valign=bottom width=11% colspan=2&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: right align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#8212;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 2.5%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=2% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 1.3%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double valign=bottom width=1% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: windowtext 1pt solid; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 9.7%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double valign=bottom width=9% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: right align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;384
778&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 1%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=1% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Considerable judgment is required in interpreting market data to develop the estimate of fair value of our derivative instruments.&amp;#160; Accordingly
 the estimate may not be indicative of the amounts that we could realize in a current market exchange.&amp;#160; The use of different market assumptions or valuation methodologies could have a material effect on the estimated fair value amounts.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Derivative Financial Instruments&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We utilize interest rate swaps in the management of our variable interest rate exposure and do not enter into derivatives for trading purposes.&amp;#160; All derivatives are measured at fair value.&amp;#160; Our interest rate swaps are classified as cash flow hedges.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Cash and Cash Equivalents&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We consider all highly liquid investments purchased with an original maturity of three months or less to be cash equivalents.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Accounts Receivable&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Accounts receivable consist primarily of receivables from customers and distributors for products purchased.&amp;#160; Receivables are past due when they are unpaid greater than thirty days.&amp;#160; We determine any required reserves by considering a number of factors
 including the length of time the accounts receivable have been outstanding
 and our loss history.&amp;#160; We maintain an allowance for doubtful accounts for estimated losses resulting from the inability of our customers to make required payments.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Inventories&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Inventories are stated at the lower of cost (first-in
 first-out) or market.&amp;#160; We identify slow moving or obsolete inventories and estimate appropriate write-down provisions related thereto.&amp;#160; If actual market conditions are less favorable than those projected by management
 additional inventory write-downs may be required.&amp;#160; In the ordinary course of business
 we manage price and supply risk of commodities by entering into various short-term purchase arrangements with our vendors.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Property and Equipment&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Property and equipment are recorded at cost.&amp;#160; Cost includes expenditures for major improvements and replacements.&amp;#160; Maintenance and repairs are charged to operations when incurred.&amp;#160; When assets are retired or otherwise disposed of
 the related costs and accumulated depreciation are removed from the appropriate accounts
 and the resulting gain or loss is recognized. &amp;#160;Depreciation expense is computed using the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets
 ranging from two to thirty years.&amp;#160; We capitalize certain computer software and software development costs incurred in connection with developing or obtaining computer software for internal use.&amp;#160; Capitalized software costs are included in property
 plant and equipment and amortized on a straight-line basis when placed into service over three years.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We evaluate the recoverability of property and equipment not held for sale by comparing the carrying amount of the asset or group of assets against the estimated undiscounted future cash flows expected to result from the use of the asset or group of assets and their eventual disposition
 in accordance with relevant authoritative guidance.&amp;#160; If the undiscounted future cash flows are less than the carrying value of the asset or group of assets being evaluated
 an impairment loss is recorded.&amp;#160; The loss is measured as the difference between the fair value and carrying value of the asset or group of assets being evaluated.&amp;#160; Assets to be disposed of are reported at the lower of the carrying amount or the fair value less cost to sell.&amp;#160; The estimated fair value would be based on the best information available under the circumstances
 including prices for similar assets or the results of valuation techniques
 including the present value of expected future cash flows using a discount rate commensurate with the risks involved.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Intangible Assets&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Goodwill and trademarks are reviewed for impairment annually or more frequently if impairment indicators arise.&amp;#160; Goodwill
 by reporting unit
 is required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change that more-likely-than-not reduces the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying value.&amp;#160; We have concluded from our annual impairment testing performed in December&amp;#160;that neither of our two reporting units were at risk of failing the impairment test in the near term
 and we believe that there are no known risks for that conclusion to change at either of our reporting units.&amp;#160; Intangible assets with indefinite lives are required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change indicating that the asset might be impaired.&amp;#160; Amortizable intangible assets are amortized using the straight-line method over their estimated useful lives
 which is the estimated period over which economic benefits are expected to be provided.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center align=center&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Management believes that each of our trademarks has the continued ability to generate cash flows indefinitely
 and therefore each of our trademarks has been determined to have an indefinite life.&amp;#160; Management&amp;#8217;s determination that our trademarks have indefinite lives includes an evaluation of historical cash flows and projected cash flows for each of these trademarks.&amp;#160; In addition
 there are no legal
 regulatory
 contractual
 economic or other factors to limit the useful life of these trademarks
 and management intends to renew each of these trademarks
 which can be accomplished at little cost.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;See Note 2 &amp;#8220;Goodwill
 Trademarks
 and Other Intangible Assets&amp;#8221; for additional information.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Self-Insurance Reserves&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We are partially self-insured for the purposes of providing health care benefits to employees covered by our insurance plan.&amp;#160; The plan covers all full-time employees of the Company on the first day of the month after hiring date for salaried employees
 and the first day of the month following the ninetieth day of service for hourly employees.&amp;#160; The plan covers the employee&amp;#8217;s dependents
 if elected by the employee.&amp;#160; We have contracted with an insurance carrier for stop loss coverage that commences when $75
000 in claims is paid annually for a covered participant.&amp;#160; In addition
 we have contracted for aggregate stop loss insurance which provides coverage after the maximum amount paid by us exceeds approximately $1.5 million.&amp;#160; Estimated unpaid claims included in accrued liabilities amount to $0.4 million and $0.3 million at December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011 respectively.&amp;#160; These amounts represent management&amp;#8217;s best estimate of amounts that have not been paid prior to the year-end dates.&amp;#160; It is reasonably possible that the expense we will ultimately incur could differ.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Revenue Recognition&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;In accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States
 we recognize operating revenues upon shipment of products to customers provided title and risk of loss pass to our customers.&amp;#160; In those instances where title and risk of loss does not pass until delivery
 revenue recognition is deferred until delivery has occurred.&amp;#160; In our snack products segment
 revenue for products sold through our local distribution network prior to the sale of this business in November&amp;#160;2012
 was recognized when the product is received by the retailer.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Provisions and allowances for sales returns
 promotional allowances
 coupon redemption and discounts are also recorded as a reduction of revenues in our consolidated financial statements.&amp;#160; These allowances are estimated based on a percentage of sales returns using historical and current market information.&amp;#160; We record certain reductions to revenue for promotional allowances.&amp;#160; There are several different types of promotional allowances such as off-invoice allowances
 rebates and shelf space allowances.&amp;#160; An off-invoice allowance is a reduction of the sales price that is directly deducted from the invoice amount.&amp;#160; We record the amount of the deduction as a reduction to revenue when the transaction occurs.&amp;#160; We record certain allowances for coupon redemptions
 scan-back promotions and other promotional activities as a reduction to revenue.&amp;#160; Anytime we offer consideration (cash or credit) as a trade advertising or promotional allowance to a purchaser of products at any point along the distribution chain
 the amount is accrued and recorded as a reduction in revenue.&amp;#160; Costs associated with obtaining shelf space (i.e.
 &amp;#8220;slotting fees&amp;#8221;) are accounted for as a reduction of revenue in the period in which we incur such costs.&amp;#160; The accrued liabilities for these allowances are monitored throughout the time period covered by the coupon or promotion.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Shipping and Handling&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Shipping and handling costs are included in cost of revenues.&amp;#160; We do not bill customers for freight.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Income Taxes&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We account for income taxes under the asset and liability method
 which requires the recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the financial statements.&amp;#160; Under this method
 deferred tax assets and liabilities are determined based on the differences between the financial statements and tax basis of assets and liabilities using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in which the differences are expected to reverse.&amp;#160; The effect of a change in tax rates on deferred tax assets and liabilities is recognized in income in the period that includes the enactment date.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We record net deferred tax assets to the extent we believe these assets will more likely than not be realized.&amp;#160; In making such determination
 we consider all available positive and negative evidence
 including future reversals of existing taxable temporary differences
 projected future taxable income
 tax planning strategies and recent financial operations.&amp;#160; Failure to achieve forecasted taxable income in applicable tax jurisdictions could affect the ultimate realization of deferred tax assets and could result in an increase in our effective tax rate on future earnings.&amp;#160; A valuation allowance is provided when it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized.&amp;#160; The authoritative guidance provides that a tax benefit from an uncertain tax position may be recognized when it is more likely than not that the position will be sustained upon examination
 including resolutions of any related appeals or litigation processes
 based on the technical merits.&amp;#160; The tax benefit is measured based on the largest benefit that has a greater than 50% likelihood of being realized upon ultimate settlement&lt;i&gt;.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;It is our policy to recognize interest and penalties accrued on any unrecognized tax benefits as a component of income tax expense.&amp;#160; We do not have any accrued interest or penalties associated with any unrecognized tax benefits
 nor was any interest or penalties recorded during the years ended December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We file income tax returns in the U.S. federal jurisdiction and various state jurisdictions.&amp;#160; Our U.S. federal income tax returns for years 2009 through 2011 remain open to examination by the Internal Revenue Service.&amp;#160; Our state tax returns for years 2008 through 2011 remain open to examination by the state jurisdictions.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Stock Options and Stock-Based Compensation&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Stock options and other stock based compensation awards expense are adjusted for estimated forfeitures and are recognized on a straight-line basis over the requisite period of the award
 which is currently one to five years for stock options
 and one to three years for restricted stock.&amp;#160; We estimate future forfeiture rates based on our historical experience.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Compensation costs related to all stock-based payment arrangements
 including employee stock options
 are recognized in the financial statements based on the fair value method of accounting.&amp;#160; Excess tax benefits related to stock-based payment arrangements are classified as cash inflows from financing activities and cash outflows from operating activities.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;See Note 8 &amp;#8220;Shareholders&amp;#8217; Equity&amp;#8221; for additional information.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Earnings Per Common Share&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Basic earnings per common share is computed by dividing net income by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period.&amp;#160; Diluted earnings per share is calculated by including all dilutive common shares such as stock options and restricted stock.&amp;#160; For the year ended December&amp;#160;29
 2012
 options to purchase 281
017 shares of our Common Stock were excluded from the calculation of diluted earnings per share because their effects were antidilutive.&amp;#160; For the year ended December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 options to purchase 215
500 shares of our Common Stock were excluded from the calculation of diluted earnings per share because their effects were antidilutive.&amp;#160; These exclusions were made because the options&amp;#8217; exercise prices were greater than the average market price of our common stock for those periods.&amp;#160; Exercises of outstanding stock options or warrants are assumed to occur for purposes of calculating diluted earnings per share for periods in which their effect would not be anti-dilutive.&amp;#160; Earnings per common share was computed as follows for the years ended December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: center align=center&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 20pt; TEXT-INDENT: -10pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Weighted average number of common shares&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 2.68%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=2% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: right align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;18
821

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 1.3%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double valign=bottom width=1% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: windowtext 2.25pt double; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 11.52%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double valign=bottom width=11% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: right align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;0.38&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 2.68%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=2% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 1.3%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double valign=bottom width=1% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: windowtext 2.25pt double; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; WIDTH: 11.52%; PADDING-TOP: 0in; BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double valign=bottom width=11% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: right align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;0.15&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; WIDTH: 1.04%; PADDING-TOP: 0in valign=bottom width=1% bgcolor=#CCEEFF&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 1pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Subsequent Events&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 30pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Subsequent events are events or transactions that occur after the balance sheet date but before financial statements are issued.&amp;#160; We recognize in the financial statements the effects of all subsequent events that provide additional evidence about conditions that existed at the date of the balance sheet
 including the estimates inherent in the process of preparing the financial statements.&amp;#160; Our financial statements do not recognize subsequent events that provide evidence about conditions that did not exist at the date of the balance sheet but arose after the balance sheet date and before financial statements are issued.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Recent Accounting Pronouncements&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;In 2011
 the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&amp;#8220;FASB&amp;#8221;) issued two Accounting Standards Updates (&amp;#8220;ASUs&amp;#8221;)
 which amend the guidance for the presentation of comprehensive income.&amp;#160; The amended guidance eliminates the option to report other comprehensive income and its components in the statement of changes in equity.&amp;#160; Upon adoption
 other comprehensive income must be presented either in a single continuous statement of comprehensive income or in two separate but consecutive statements.&amp;#160; Although the new guidance changes the presentation of comprehensive income
 there are no changes to the components that are recognized in comprehensive income.&amp;#160; We adopted these ASUs in 2012 using two separate but consecutive statements.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;In July&amp;#160;2012
 the FASB issued new impairment testing requirements for indefinite-lived intangible assets.&amp;#160; Under the updated standard an entity would first perform a qualitative impairment test for indefinite-lived intangible assets to determine whether a quantitative assessment is necessary. The requirements are effective for annual and interim impairment tests for fiscal years beginning after September&amp;#160;15
 2012.&amp;#160; The Company adopted the requirements during fiscal year 2012
 but elected to continue to perform a quantitative impairment analysis for our indefinite-lived intangibles.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Marketing Costs&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;We recorded $0.9 million and $1.0 million
 in fiscal years 2012 and 2011 respectively
 for advertising costs which are included in selling
 general and administrative expenses on the Consolidated Statements of Operations.&amp;#160; These costs include various sponsorships
 coupon administration and consumer advertising programs that we enter into throughout the year
 and are expensed as incurred.&amp;#160; We are a national co-sponsor of American Rivers
 a leading conservation organization protecting and restoring America&amp;#8217;s rivers.&amp;#160; We are allowed to use the American Rivers mark on packaging and printed materials as well as directly promote products to members and river cleanup volunteers.&amp;#160; Our marketing programs also include selective event sponsorship designed to increase brand awareness and to provide opportunities to mass sample branded products.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman size=2&gt;Also included in selling
 general and administrative expense are costs and fees relating to the execution of in-store product demonstrations with club stores or grocery retailers
 which were $1.9 million and $3.6 million for the years ended December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 respectively.&amp;#160; The cost of product used in the demonstrations
 which is insignificant
 and the fee we pay to the independent third party providers who conduct the in-store demonstrations
 are recorded as expense when the event occurs.&amp;#160; Product demonstrations are conducted by independent third party providers designated by the various retailer or club chains.&amp;#160; During the in-store demonstrations
 the consumers in the stores receive small samples of our products
 and consumers are not required to purchase our product in order to receive the sample.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

 which is a bank's commitment to make loans up to a specific amount. Examples of items that might be included in the application of this element may consist of letters of credit

 or (b) the enterprise has entered into a financing agreement that clearly permits the enterprise to refinance the short-term obligation on a long term basis and the following conditions are met (1) the agreement does not expire within 1 year and is not cancelable by the lender except for violation of an objectively determinable provision
 (2) no violation exists at the BS date
 and (3) the lender has entered into the financing agreement is expected to be financially capable of honoring the agreement.

Goodwill and trademarks are reviewed for impairment annually in the fourth fiscal quarter
 or more frequently if impairment indicators arise.&#160; Goodwill is required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change that more-likely-than-not reduces the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying value.&#160; Intangible assets with indefinite lives are required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change indicating that the asset might be impaired.&#160; We believe the carrying values of our intangible assets are appropriate.





        
          

        
          
            

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 which may include (a) for amortizable intangible assets (also referred to as finite-lived intangible assets)
 the carrying amount
 the amount of any significant residual value
 and the weighted-average amortization period
 (b) for intangible assets not subject to amortization (also referred to as indefinite-lived intangible assets)
 the carrying amount
 and (c) the amount of research and development assets acquired and written off in the period
 including the line item in the income statement in which the amounts written off are aggregated
 if not readily apparent from the income statement. Also discloses (a) for amortizable intangibles assets in total and by major class
 the gross carrying amount and accumulated amortization
 the total amortization expense for the period
 and the estimated aggregate amortization expense for each of the five succeeding fiscal years
 (b) for intangible assets not subject to amortization the carrying amount in total and by major class
 and (c) for goodwill
 in total and for each reportable segment
 the changes in the carrying amount of goodwill during the period (including the aggregate amount of goodwill acquired
 the aggregate amount of impairment losses recognized
 and the amount of goodwill included in the gain (loss) on disposal of a reporting unit). If any part of goodwill has not been allocated to a reportable segment
 discloses the unallocated amount and the reasons for not allocating. For each impairment loss recognized related to an intangible asset (excluding goodwill)
 discloses: (a) a description of the impaired intangible asset and the facts and circumstances leading to the impairment
 (b) the amount of the impairment loss and the method for determining fair value
 (c) the caption in the income statement or the statement of activities in which the impairment loss is aggregated
 and (d) the segment in which the impaired intangible asset is reported. For each goodwill impairment loss recognized
 discloses: (a) a description of the facts and circumstances leading to the impairment
 (b) the amount of the impairment loss and the method of determining the fair value of the associated reporting unit
 and (c) if a recognized impairment loss is an estimate not finalized and the reasons why the estimate is not final.  May also disclose the nature and amount of any significant adjustments made to a previous estimate of an impairment loss.

Organization
 Business and Summary of Significant Accounting Policies:

        

      






Organization
 Business and Summary of Significant Accounting Policies:
        


Organization
 Business and Summary of Significant Accounting Policies:
        
Organization
 Business and Summary of Significant Accounting Policies:

Inventure Foods
&#160;Inc.
 a Delaware corporation (the &#8220;Company
&#8221; referred to as &#8220;we&#8221; &#8220;our&#8221; or &#8220;us&#8221;)
 is a $185+ million leading marketer and manufacturer of healthy/natural and indulgent specialty snack food brands.

Our goal is to build a rapidly growing specialty brand company that specializes in evolving consumer eating habits in two primary product segments: 1) Healthy/Natural Food Products 2) Indulgent Specialty Snack Food Brands.&#160; We sell our products nationally through a number of channels including: Grocery
 Natural
 Mass Merchandisers
 Drug
 Club
 Vending
 Food Service
 Convenience Stores and International.&#160; Our goal is to have a diversified portfolio of brands
 products
 customers and distribution channels.

In the healthy/natural portfolio
 products include Rader Farms frozen berries
 Boulder Canyon Natural Foods&#174; brand kettle cooked potato chips
 Jamba&#174; branded blend-and-serve smoothie kits under license from Jamba Juice Company and private label frozen fruit and healthy/natural snacks.&#160; In November&#160;2012
 we entered into a license agreement with Seattle&#8217;s Best Coffee LLC
 and launched a line of blend-and-serve frozen coffee drink kits.&#160; Production and distribution of these products are scheduled to begin during the first quarter of 2013.

In the Indulgent Specialty category
 products include T.G.I. Friday&#8217;s&#174; brand snacks under license from T.G.I. Friday&#8217;s Inc.
 BURGER KING&#8482;&#160;brand snack products under license from Burger King Corporation
 Nathan&#8217;s Famous&#174; brand snack products under license from Nathan&#8217;s Famous Corporation
 Vidalia&#174; brand snack products under license from Vidalia Brands
&#160;Inc.
 Poore Brothers&#174; kettle cooked potato chips
 Bob&#8217;s Texas Style&#174; kettle cooked chips
 and Tato Skins&#174; brand potato snacks.&#160; Our license to sell Burger King&#8482; brand snacks products expired December&#160;31
 2012.&#160; We also manufacture private label snacks for certain grocery retail chains and distribute snack food products in Arizona that are manufactured by others.

We own and operate manufacturing facilities in three locations.&#160; Our snack products are manufactured at the Arizona and Indiana plants as well as some third party plants for certain products.&#160; Our frozen berry products are manufactured by our wholly-owned subsidiary Rader Farms
&#160;Inc.
 a Delaware Corporation (&#8220;Rader Farms&#8221;).&#160;&#160;Rader Farms grows
 processes and markets premium berry blends
 raspberries
 blueberries
 and rhubarb and purchases marionberries
 cherries
 cranberries
 strawberries and other fruits from a select network of fruit growers for resale.&#160; The fruit is processed
 frozen and packaged for sale and distribution to wholesale customers.&#160; We also use third party processors for certain products.

On November&#160;5
 2012
 we sold our Direct-Store-Delivery (DSD) business for $1.2 million in cash
 which primarily covered a network of independently operated and owned service routes and limited fixed assets associated with the DSD business.&#160; We received an additional $0.3 million for inventory on-hand.&#160; We recognized a net gain of $1.1 million in continuing operations as we will continue to indirectly sell our products through this network at a reduced cost and will no longer sell distributed products.&#160; 2012 sales of distributed products were $2.6 million.&#160; Our DSD business was part of our Snack segment and included a limited number of snack food products purchased and sold through our DSD network in Arizona.

Our fiscal year ends on the last Saturday occurring in the month of December&#160;of each calendar year.&#160; Accordingly
 the fiscal year end dates result in an additional week of results every five or six years.&#160; Fiscal year 2012 commenced January&#160;1
 2012 and ended December&#160;29
 2012
 resulting in a 52 week fiscal year.&#160; Fiscal year 2011 commenced December&#160;26
 2010 ended December&#160;31
 2011
 resulting in a 53 week fiscal year.



The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of Inventure Foods
&#160;Inc. and all of its wholly owned subsidiaries.&#160; All significant intercompany amounts and transactions have been eliminated.



The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities
 disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements
 and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period.&#160; We routinely evaluate our estimates
 including those related to accruals for customer programs and incentives
 product returns
 bad debts
 income taxes
 long-lived assets
 inventories
 stock based compensation
 interest rate swap valuations
 accrued broker commissions and contingencies.&#160; We base our estimates on historical experience and on various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable under the circumstances.&#160; Actual results could differ from those estimates.



Fair value is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability (i.e.
 the &#8220;exit price&#8221;)&#160; in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date.&#160; W

Unadjusted quoted prices in active markets that are accessible at the measurement date for identical
 unrestricted assets or liabilities;

Quoted prices in markets that are not considered to be active or financial instruments without quoted market prices
 but for which all significant inputs are observable
 either directly or indirectly;





At December&#160;29
 2012 and December&#160;31
 2011
 the carrying value of cash
 accounts receivable
 accounts payable and accrued liabilities approximate fair values since they are short-term in nature.&#160; The carrying value of the long-term debt approximates fair-value based on the borrowing rates currently available to us for long-term borrowings with similar terms.
